# Files embedded into the compiler binary via `include_str!` MUST stay LF.
#
# Rust string/raw-string literals normalize CRLF->LF at compile time, but
# `include_str!` is byte-verbatim — so on a Windows checkout (autocrlf), a CRLF
# runtime template would leak CRLF into all generated server/client code and
# break codegen's string-replace machinery (the `//__XERES_*__` placeholders).
# Pinning these to LF makes the build reproducible across platforms.
/runtime/** text eol=lf
/std/** text eol=lf
*.xrs text eol=lf
